title: How does frost cover protect garden plants?
content: Frost cover for plants acts as a protective shield against harsh cold temperatures, preventing frost damage that can harm delicate leaves, buds, and blooms. By trapping heat from the soil and blocking freezing winds, it creates a warmer microclimate around plants. This insulation helps reduce ice crystals from forming on plant tissues, which often leads to wilting or death. Frost covers are lightweight, breathable, and allow air and moisture circulation, ensuring plants remain healthy. Gardeners often use them during unexpected frosts in fall or spring, making them an essential tool for extending growing seasons successfully.

title: Google Not Contained by Container Tab
content:
I am noticing what I think is a bug with Google and Firefox Container tabs.

Currently: If I have a non-google site open in a particular container tab (say, LinkedIn.com on a LinkedIn container tab that I've designated as green colored), and then I make another new tab in that same container, and I type in google.com, Firefox automatically switches the tab type from the green LinkedIn container tab type to a colorless no-container tab, and, on top of that, because I am signed in to google in my no-container tab, it signs me in to my account.

Expected: When I open a new tab in a container, and I go to google.com, that the Firefox tab remain in that green container tab type and not switch me to a different tab type where I'm signed in to Google and it's tracking me.

Note: I am not looking for workarounds -- I have already been able to work around it myself. Rather, I am trying to report this as a bug.

title: Outlook Office on Firefox keeps kicking me off
content:
Sometimes when I sign in on Microsoft Outlook's email portal - a multistep process requiring authentication on one's phone - it says: "Hang on a minute while we sign you out" and then boots me, forcing me to sign in again. For awhile this was happening only occasionally, and the workaround was to delete all cookies for Microsoft online and Office. But now this is happening more frequently, and sometimes it happens immediately after deleting the cookies. In effect, Outlook on Firefox creates cookies that then prevent it from working. And it doesn't matter whether you say yes or no to "Stay signed in?" at the end of the sign-in process.

I reached out to Microsoft tech support, and they basically said this is a Firefox issue because it doesn't happen on Chrome or Edge.

Anyone else encounter this?

title: Contact Number Not Visible on My Website in Firefox – Rama Rehab
content:
Hello Mozilla Support Team,

I’m facing an issue where the contact number on my website is not visible when viewed in Firefox, while it displays correctly in other browsers like Chrome, Safari, and Edge.

My business is called Rama Rehab, a Rehabilitation Centre in Delhi, and it's crucial for visitors to see our phone number for inquiries and bookings. The number is embedded in the site header/footer (or contact section), but for some reason, Firefox either hides it or fails to render it correctly.

Website: https://www.ramarehab.com/ What I’ve tried:

Cleared browser cache

Disabled all extensions

Checked in Private Window

Ensured number is not blocked by content settings

Still, the issue persists. Could this be related to content blocking, font issues, CSS rendering, or any privacy-related settings in Firefox?

Please help me understand what might be causing this and how to resolve it.

Thanks in advance, Rama Rehab
creator: roarwellnessrama
